== Brain Energy Metabolism: Cross-Disease Convergent Framework
<sec:brain-energy-cross-disease>

The energy metabolism abnormalities documented in ME/CFS peripheral tissues --- impaired OXPHOS, glycolytic shift, elevated lactate --- converge with cerebral metabolic findings to suggest a brain energy deficit that may directly drive cognitive symptoms. This section synthesizes evidence from ME/CFS neuroimaging and cross-disease models to propose that brain energy metabolism dysfunction is not merely a downstream consequence of systemic illness but a central mechanism contributing to cognitive dysfunction, sensory processing deficits, and the selective impairment of energy-demanding CNS-coordinated processes.

#speculation(title: [Astrocyte-Mediated Brain Energy Conservation as Cognitive Dysfunction Mechanism])[
*Certainty: 0.40.* Blagojevic-Stokic et al. (2026) proposed a comprehensive brain energy disorder model for autism spectrum disorder (ASD) in which astrocytic glucose metabolism dysfunction --- impaired glucose uptake, glycogen storage failure, and disrupted astrocyte-neuron lactate shuttling --- produces suboptimal ATP availability in the brain @BlagojevicStokic2026brainenergy. Their model posits an "energy-saving adaptation": the brain economizes by deprioritizing higher-order, energy-intensive processes (social communication, cognitive flexibility, sensory integration) to preserve ATP for basic survival functions. Independently, Lacourt et al. (2018) developed a structurally identical model for ME/CFS fatigue: chronic low-grade inflammation → reduced cellular energy availability → non-adaptive energy conservation as fatigue mechanism @Lacourt2018InflammationEnergy. The two models, derived from different disease contexts without cross-reference, converge on the same mechanistic logic: energy deficit drives cognitive and behavioural sacrifice.

*ME/CFS evidence.* ME/CFS independently exhibits the core biochemical features of the ASD brain energy model: (1) regional brain glucose hypometabolism on FDG-PET (Siessmeier et al., 2003, n=26; Van Der Gucht et al., 2017, n=24 MMF with CFS-like symptoms) @siessmeier2003pet @VanDerGucht2017MMFFDG; (2) elevated ventricular lactate on MRS indicating cerebral glycolytic shift away from OXPHOS (Natelson et al., 2017, n=34 CFS) @Natelson2017Lactate; (3) astrocyte dysfunction implicated in central fatigue pathways (Morris & Maes, 2015) @Morris2015CentralPathways; and (4) a comprehensive 2026 brain-centered cognitive dysfunction framework that explicitly includes astrocytic glucose metabolism and lactate shuttle disruption (Xu et al., 2026) @Xu2026Neurovascular. Zhu et al. (2025) synthesized FDG-PET, MRS, and mitochondrial evidence into a convergent cerebral metabolic signature in ME/CFS @Zhu2025MetabolicNeuroimaging. (Certainty: 0.40 --- the individual components are independently supported, but the assembled framework is a mechanistic inference across studies; no direct study has simultaneously measured brain glucose, brain lactate, astrocyte function, and cognitive performance in the same ME/CFS cohort.)

*Parallel to ASD model.* In both conditions, prefrontal cortex (PFC) appears particularly vulnerable: this region has the highest metabolic rate in the human brain, the highest glycolysis/OXPHOS pathway expression, and the greatest astrocyte specialisation. ME/CFS patients show reduced activation in PFC-dependent cognitive tasks and impaired cognitive flexibility --- the same domain predicted to fail first under energy constraint. The ASD model's "energy-saving barter" --- sacrificing cognitive flexibility, novel information processing, and social engagement to preserve ATP for survival functions --- maps precisely onto ME/CFS cognitive symptoms: brain fog as reduced information processing capacity, impaired task-switching as cognitive rigidity under energy constraint, and sensory overload as inability to filter irrelevant stimuli without sufficient ATP for inhibitory networks.

*Limitations.* The ASD model is neurodevelopmental; ME/CFS is acquired. GLUT1 deficiency syndrome provides proof-of-concept that impaired brain glucose transport produces ASD-like deficits, but no GLUT1 data exist in ME/CFS. PFC-specific glucose metabolism has not been studied in ME/CFS.

*Falsifiable prediction.* (1) Hyperpolarized #super[13]C-MRS will demonstrate reduced glucose-to-lactate conversion rate in ME/CFS PFC during cognitive tasks. (2) Ketogenic diet will improve cognitive scores in ME/CFS patients with documented brain hypometabolism. (3) ME/CFS patients will show steeper cognitive decline during prolonged testing (≥ 60 min).
] <spec:astrocyte-brain-energy-conservation>

#open-question(title: [Is Brain Glucose Hypometabolism in ME/CFS Primary or Secondary?])[
ME/CFS brain glucose hypometabolism is documented but its causal status is unresolved. Four models: (1) primary metabolic (astrocyte/neuron intrinsic OXPHOS/glycolysis defect), (2) perfusion-limited (cerebral hypoperfusion reduces substrate delivery), (3) inflammation-masked (microglial activation consumes glucose masking neuronal deficit), (4) compensatory downregulation (adaptive response to systemic energy constraint). These models are not mutually exclusive. Distinguishing them requires simultaneous #super[13]C-MRS (glucose-to-lactate flux) with CBF measurement, TSPO-PET for microglial glucose consumption, and ketone-body MRS to test whether neurons can utilize alternative fuels.
] <oq:brain-hypometabolism-primary-vs-secondary>

#open-question(title: [Can Ketogenic Diet Improve ME/CFS Cognitive Symptoms via Brain Energy Restoration?])[
The ASD brain energy model identifies ketogenic diet as therapeutic proof-of-concept: ketone bodies bypass glycolysis and PDC blockade → direct TCA entry @BlagojevicStokic2026brainenergy. ME/CFS-specific clinical data are limited to case reports (n=1) @Zarnowska2018KD and ASD trials (not ME/CFS) @Lee2018modifiedKD. Key unknowns: (1) Does brain ketone uptake differ in ME/CFS? (2) Is improvement proportional to baseline hypometabolism? (3) Does effect depend on hypometabolism being metabolic vs perfusion-limited? (4) Can exogenous ketone esters test the mechanism without full dietary change --- critical for severe patients?
] <oq:ketogenic-diet-brain-energy>

=== Limitations of the ASD-ME/CFS Brain Energy Convergence

#limitation(title: [Brain Hypometabolism May Be Epiphenomenon, Not Mechanism])[
*Origin: brainstorm.* Shared FDG-PET and MRS patterns between ASD and ME/CFS could be epiphenomenal to: (1) physical deconditioning, (2) sleep disruption, or (3) systemic inflammation — each would produce indistinguishable metabolic patterns without any GLUT1/astrocytic bottleneck. No study has ruled out these alternative explanations in ME/CFS.
]

#limitation(title: [No Direct Astrocytic Evidence in ME/CFS])[
*Origin: brainstorm.* Astrocytic GLUT1/ANLS failure has never been directly tested in ME/CFS. FDG-PET measures summed glucose uptake across all cell types. MRS measures bulk tissue metabolites. No ME/CFS study has quantified astrocytic GLUT1 or measured ANLS function. The evidence is entirely indirect.
]

#open-question(title: [Null Hypothesis: Brain Metabolism Does Not Differ Between ME/CFS and Other Fatigue Conditions])[
*Origin: brainstorm.* Does ME/CFS brain metabolism differ from depression-associated fatigue, MS fatigue, or post-cancer fatigue? All show frontal/basal ganglia hypometabolism — overlapping with ME/CFS. Candidate ME/CFS-specific differentiators: low CSF:plasma glucose ratio, astrocyte-specific metabolic markers, correlation between brain metabolism and PEM. A head-to-head comparison study is needed.
] <oq:brain-metabolism-specificity-fatigue>

=== Speculative Brain Energy Interventions

#speculation(title: [Ketone Esters + MCT Oil for Brain Glucose Bypass in ME/CFS])[
*Certainty: 0.30. Probability of clinically meaningful efficacy in ME/CFS: 0.06. Origin: brainstorm.* If GLUT1-mediated brain glucose transport is impaired, ketone bodies provide an alternative fuel entering via MCT1 rather than GLUT1 — directly bypassing the bottleneck. Ketone esters (15--30 g/day) + MCT oil (2--4 tbsp/day) raise blood BHB to 2--5 mM within 30 minutes. MCT oil also promotes astrocytic lactate production (C10 decanoic acid) @Andersen2021MCTastrocytes. No ME/CFS-specific trial data.

*Severity applicability:* All levels. Severe: micro-dose MCT (¼ tsp, titrate). Very severe: ketone esters if tolerated; environmental energy conservation may be primary.

*Falsifiable prediction.* ME/CFS patients with documented prefrontal FDG-PET hypometabolism who achieve blood BHB ≥ 0.5 mM will show cognitive improvement proportional to baseline hypometabolism severity.
] <spec:ketone-esters-mct-bypass>

#open-question(title: [CSF:Plasma Glucose Ratio as GLUT1 Bottleneck Biomarker in ME/CFS])[
*Origin: brainstorm.* The clinical test for GLUT1 deficiency syndrome is CSF:plasma glucose ratio (normal ≥ 0.60 children). If ME/CFS involves functional GLUT1 impairment at the blood-brain barrier, patients should show reduced CSF:plasma glucose ratio. This has never been measured. A single lumbar puncture study (n=30 each) with paired glucose measurement could define a treatable ME/CFS subtype. If 20--40% show ratios below 0.50, this would parallel GLUT1 deficiency syndrome and support ketogenic diet as targeted therapy.
] <oq:csf-plasma-glucose-ratio>

#open-question(title: [GLUT1 Deficiency Syndrome as Monogenic ME/CFS Model])[
*Origin: brainstorm.* GLUT1 deficiency syndrome (G1D, SLC2A1 mutation) causes impaired BBB glucose transport → epilepsy, cognitive delay, ASD-like deficits — reversible with ketogenic diet. G1D is a monogenic analogue to the hypothesized ME/CFS brain glucose transport failure. Key questions: (1) Do adults with milder G1D variants report ME/CFS-like symptoms? (2) Could SLC2A1 common variants constitute ME/CFS genetic predisposition (testable in DecodeME, n > 17,000)? (3) Do G1D registries capture fatigue, PEM, and orthostatic intolerance? G1D provides a causal-anchor model for the GLUT1 bottleneck hypothesis.
] <oq:glut1-deficiency-mecfs-model>

#speculation(title: [Severity-Adapted Brain Energy Restoration Protocol])[
*Certainty: 0.20. Probability of clinically meaningful efficacy in ME/CFS: 0.04. Origin: brainstorm.* Brain energy interventions require severity-adapted protocols. Mild: ketone esters 15 g/day + MCT 1 tbsp + cognitive pacing. Moderate: reduced doses + pre-dose before exertion. Severe: micro-dose MCT (¼ tsp), neuroprotection only. Very severe: environmental energy conservation (dark, quiet, minimal sensory input), ketones if tolerated.

*Falsifiable prediction.* Severity-adapted protocols will show differential tolerance: moderate patients tolerate full doses with cognitive improvement; severe patients tolerate micro-doses with stabilization; very-severe may not tolerate oral interventions.
] <spec:severity-adapted-brain-energy>
